I'm a bit torn on this. What you have suggested provides the most flexibility for users but patching in a classmethod or bound method requires an unintuitive signature. And patching an unbound method is similarly unintuitive. However I'm inclined to agree that this is simple, provided users understand the distinctions between functions and bound and unbound methods.

I think what pushes me over the edge to thinking your table is the way to go is considering the case where someone wants to patch staticmethod foo() with classmethod bar(cls) which would lead to the following if we just did simple replacemnt:

```
class A(object):
    @staticmethod
    def foo():
        pass
class B(object):
    @classmethod
    def bar():
        pass
class C(object):
    @classmethod
    def bar(cls):
        pass
```

A.foo could be patched with B.bar because the signatures match, but B.bar() would not be valid. And although C.bar() is valid you could not patch A.foo with it. Other combinations have the same issues. So the increase in power of your suggestion leads me to favor it despite the additional complexity inherent in some cases.


It would probably be very useful to have your table somewhere in the docs for reference.

